      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;14.23 The Criminal&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-22-the-end-of-quarantine-life/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was a creature whose curiosity would win over troublesomeness. Thus, she was walking on cold stone, heading down a narrow, dark, and damp underground path.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She was in the prison. A place for those who had committed crimes that no one would wish to improve.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The sound of footsteps echoed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Don’t make eye contact with the criminals,” Rihaku cautioned her.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Given the location, he made the better choice of guide than Chue. Chue may be tough and stronger than any common guard, but she looked like a sloppy attendant with her one disabled arm. It was correct to pick guards that were big and brawny to not be slighted by rough people. The other two guards were also chosen for their large build.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The voices of the criminals sounded like curses. The things being said when they saw Maomao’s group passing through were nothing good. Even if they were showering contemptuous and obscene words, the criminals had no way of leaving their cells. They didn’t sound well either.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The sounds of coughing. Their glazed eyes had no signs of vitality.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao understood this was a prison for the ill.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao covered her mouth with a towel. Rihaku and the others did the same. It didn’t give her a pleasant feeling to abandon the sick, but she mustn’t show compassion here—Maomao ignored the voices around her.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s this one.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was one of the narrow solitary cells. A man was lying on a worn-out mat. He had a torn piece of cloth draped over him in place of a blanket.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;There was an air vent to allow ventilation. Shivering from the draught, the prisoner could only curl up into a ball.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;A man who could shiver in the cold. That was the head of Yo’s village and the witch doctor.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;One of the guards made a disgusted face as he opened the cell and roused the prisoner inside.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;He smells of death.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Living creatures give off a characteristic smell when they die. A trace of that smell was already coming from the prisoner’s body.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rihaku aimed the light over.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sunken eye sockets and leathery skin. Fingers that looked black and necrotic.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;&amp;#8211;”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The prisoner couldn’t articulate. His body was fully paralysed. Pockmarks were visible on his head.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Why did you attempt to spread the smallpox vaccination, the seeds of smallpox, around?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“—a, haha.” The prisoner started to laugh. It was a strained laugh, like he was squeezing out the last of his energy for it. “Hahaha, why am I the ‘ad ‘erson?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The prisoner’s voice was muffled.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I wan’ed to copy that guy, ‘o’u’you.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It seems like he was talking about Kokuyou.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That guy, he’s a houkou, you know.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Houkou.” For some reason, that was the only word she could pick out clearly.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hahahaa, haa…” The prisoner laughed, then his thread snapped.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The guard rushed over to lift up the prisoner.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is he alive?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Barely,” the guard replied.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Would the prisoner die here without giving a proper testimony? The prisoner’s crimes were too heavy for him to expire on top of a warm mattress.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao studied the hand of the prisoner who was laid on the mat.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Houkou.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Houkou for public duty, houkou for direction, houkou for howl, houkou for  perfume…&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Houkou for &lt;/em&gt;penghou&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The name of a mythical creature came to mind.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The thousand-year tree spirit. Although the legend differed depending on the region, the one that Maomao knew was a creature close to a tree spirit. When you face the mountains and call out, it would echo back at you.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She understood what was meant by calling Kokuyou the tree spirit.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou always interacted with Maomao with a foolish smile. He would foolishly talk about his misfortunate life story, looking like he wasn’t affected by it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A tree spirit, huh?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao clenched her fists.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s wrong, Lass?” Rihaku asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Nothing. I was just thinking if I can also visit Kokuyou after this,” she replied.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That is not my call to make, but I can pass the message over to Chue, if that’s okay?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That would be helpful.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rihaku had a good sense. As soon as they left the prison, he caught hold of a subordinate and had them look for the elusive Chue.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But I do wonder what on earth Chue-san is up to this time. She even dragged a subordinate of mine into this.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is your subordinate Ujun-san?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s the guy. Also, it must have messed around with Master Basen in various ways.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yeah.” She heard that Ujun was forcibly involved to support his half-sister or something.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I’ve no clue as to why, but Ujun’s half-sister, the one who was in the inner palace before, the former consort who retired to religion, what was her name again?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Lishu-sama.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ah, that’s right. It seems that consort has returned to the U residence.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Why?” All sorts of talks have proceeded during the time Maomao was away.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No idea, but the rumours were that the U family head had strongly requested for it. Apparently the temple where Lishu-sama stayed at was doing all sorts of new things.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Was it something dangerous?” If Maomao’s hypothesis was correct, it had to be the experiment to attenuate the smallpox vaccination.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Probably. From how things have gone, it seems Lishu-sama had already been allowed to return home.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The emperor treated Lishu dearly. Her being made to leave the inner palace and retire to religion as well, had been done to prevent her from being treated unjustly.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Her father, who was both her parent and enemy, and her older half-sister had already been expelled from the U family. It should be fine for her to be called back with any reason now. Others might complain about her moving back to her maiden home again, but for Lishu, it was an old matter.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;How her future would go will depend on Basen.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;While Maomao was deep in thought, they arrived at the medical office.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao-san, Maomao-san.” The elusive Chue was already standing in front of the medical office.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rihaku waved goodbye, then returned to his previous job. Maomao bowed her head and headed over to Chue.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What is it, Chue-san?” &lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“How did it go?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“How, you ask. He only has a few days of life left. I probably won’t be able to extend his life even if I were to get involved.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. I guess so. He was caught red-handed, so he is clearly a criminal whether he lives or dies. But, it does leave a bad taste in your mouth,” Chue said indifferently. She must have known from the start and sent Maomao over. She didn’t order Maomao to examine or nurse him, which was why Maomao could only look at him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Do you know why he stabbed Kokuyou-san, why he acted as the random attackeeer?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;More or less.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao had ended up knowing.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;But this was only just speculation.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s so like Maomao-san to say nothing even if you knooow.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“As you say.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, shall we go visit Kokuyou-san to verify your answeeer?” Chue pulled Maomao’s hand to urge her.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;T/N: Houkou&amp;#8230; all of those were homonyms. I&amp;#8217;m keeping Penghou as Houkou because of that, but letting you guys know that every Houkou from here on out will refer to the Penghou.&lt;/sup&gt; &lt;sup&gt;The wiki article only talks about how they taste like dog meat, so I didn&amp;#8217;t bother linking it. Might be better to google Yamabiko to know what Maomao was talking about.&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;Also, I hope no one here minds that I translated youkai as mythical creature hahaha&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/"&gt;Next Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-23-the-criminal/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5340-67bf3f3e34154' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20250226#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5340&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5340-67bf3f3e34154' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5340-67bf3f3e34154' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-23-the-criminal/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
